  "prompt": "Why did Marco Arment sell Instapaper?",
  "response": "Marco Arment, the creator of Instapaper, sold the popular read-it-later service in April 2013 to Betaworks, a company known for its involvement in various digital media and technology ventures. Arment cited several reasons for selling Instapaper:\n\n1. **Focus on Other Projects**: Arment wanted to concentrate on other personal projects and ventures. At the time, he was involved in other software development work and wanted to dedicate his energy to new ideas.\n\n2. **Lack of Time and Resources**: Managing and growing a service like Instapaper required significant time and resources. Arment felt that he could not give it the attention it deserved while balancing other commitments.\n\n3. **Strategic Fit with Betaworks**: He believed that Betaworks would be a good home for Instapaper because of their expertise in digital media and their ability to invest in and grow the platform.\n\nAfter the sale, Instapaper continued to evolve under Betaworks' stewardship. In 2016, Pinterest acquired Instapaper from Betaworks, intending to integrate it into its ecosystem. However, in 2018, Pinterest announced it would spin off Instapaper into an independent company, returning control to a team led by the original founders, including Arment, who briefly rejoined to help transition the service.\n\nArment's decision to sell Instapaper was primarily driven by his desire to focus on new challenges and opportunities while ensuring that the service remained in capable hands.",
